0'); }\n   122→  function isZWire(w: string) { return /^z\\d+$/.test(w); }\n   123→  function isXYWire(w: string) { return /^[xy]\\d+$/.test(w); }\n   124→\n   125→  const swapped = new Set<string>();\n   126→\n   127→  // Check each gate output for violations\n   128→  for (const gate of gates) {\n   129→    const out = gate.out;\n   130→    const in1 = gate.in1;\n   131→    const in2 = gate.in2;\n   132→\n   133→    // RULE: XOR gate reading (xN, yN) for N > 0 should NOT output a z-wire\n   134→    if (gate.op === 'XOR' && isXYWire(in1) && isXYWire(in2)) {\n   135→      const xMatch = in1.match(/^x(\\d+)$/) ?? in2.match(/^x(\\d+)$/);\n   136→      if (xMatch) {\n   137→        const bit = parseInt(xMatch[1]);\n   138→        if (bit > 0 && isZWire(out)) {\n   139→          swapped.add(out);\n   140→        }\n   141→      }\n   142→    }\n   143→\n   144→    // RULE: OR gate should NOT output a z-wire (except the final carry)\n   145→    if (gate.op === 'OR' && isZWire(out)) {\n   146→      // Check if it's the final carry: final carry = z(numBits)\n   147→      const finalCarry = `z${pad(numBits)}`;\n   148→      if (out !== finalCarry) {\n   149→        swapped.add(out);\n   150→      }\n   151→    }\n   152→\n   153→    // RULE: AND gate should NOT output a z-wire\n   154→    if (gate.op === 'AND' && isZWire(out)) {\n   155→      swapped.add(out);\n   156→    }\n   157→  }\n   158→\n   159→  // Now check z-wires: each zN should be produced by the right type of gate\n   160→  for (let bit = 0; bit < numBits + 1; bit++) {\n   161→    const zN = `z${pad(bit)}`;\n   162→    const gate = byOut.get(zN);\n   163→    if (!gate) continue;\n   164→\n   165→    if (bit === 0) {\n   166→      // z00 must come from XOR(x00, y00)\n   167→      if (!(gate.op === 'XOR' && isXYWire(gate.in1) && isXYWire(gate.in2))) {\n   168→        swapped.add(zN);\n   169→      }\n   170→    } else if (bit === numBits) {\n   171→      // Final carry must come from OR gate\n   172→      if (gate.op !== 'OR') {\n   173→        swapped.add(zN);\n   174→      }\n   175→    } else {\n   176→      // zN (0 < N < numBits) must come from XOR gate\n   177→      if (gate.op !== 'XOR') {\n   178→        swapped.add(zN);\n   179→      }\n   180→      // And that XOR must have one input from XOR(xN, yN)\n   181→      if (gate.op === 'XOR') {\n   182→        const xN = `x${pad(bit)}`;\n   183→        const yN = `y${pad(bit)}`;\n   184→        const gateA = findGate('XOR', xN, yN);\n   185→        if (gateA) {\n   186→          // One of gate.in1, gate.in2 should be gateA.out\n   187→          if (gate.in1 !== gateA.out && gate.in2 !== gateA.out) {\n   188→            swapped.add(zN);\n   189→          }\n   190→        }\n   191→      }\n   192→    }\n   193→  }\n   194→\n   195→  // The wrongly identified wires must be in swap pairs.\n   196→  // Some already have partners (e.g., OR outputs z-wire: that z-wire is also flagged).\n   197→  // Find the partners for any remaining unfound swaps.\n   198→  // Since we know exactly 4 pairs, we should have 8 wires total.\n   199→  // But we might have some without partners explicitly found.\n   200→  //\n   201→  // For each wrong wire, find its swap partner:\n   202→  // - If wire W has wrong output from gate G, the correct output for G is some wire X\n   203→  //   where X is being produced by a different gate that \"should\" produce W.\n   204→  //\n   205→  // More specific: if the z00 gate is not XOR(x00,y00), then the correct gate for z00\n   206→  // is XOR(x00,y00), which is outputting some wrong wire. That wrong wire is z00's swap.\n   207→\n   208→  // Find partners for orphaned swapped wires\n   209→  const swappedArr = [...swapped];\n   210→  const partnered = new Set<string>();\n   211→\n   212→  for (const w of swappedArr) {\n   213→    if (partnered.has(w)) continue;\n   214→    // Try to find its swap partner\n   215→    const gate = byOut.get(w);\n   216→    if (!gate) continue;\n   217→\n   218→    // For each flagged wire, determine what the gate SHOULD output:\n   219→    // If gate is OR and wrongly outputs z-wire, it should output a carry.\n   220→    // The correct carry wire is the one that the next bit's final sum XOR reads.\n   221→    // If gate is AND and outputs z-wire, it should output an intermediate.\n   222→    // If z-wire is produced by wrong gate type, the correct gate is the one that\n   223→    // produces the \"correct\" wire.\n   224→\n   225→    // Pattern: XOR(xN,yN) outputs z-wire → swapped with some non-z wire\n   226→    // that XOR(xN,yN) should output.\n   227→    // That non-z wire is the one actually used as partial sum.\n   228→    // How to find it: look for what feeds into the final sum XOR at bit N.\n   229→    // The final sum XOR for bit N: XOR gate outputting zN.\n   230→    // It has two inputs: one is some non-x,y wire (the partial), one is carry.\n   231→    // The partial should be XOR(xN,yN).out.\n   232→\n   233→    if (gate.op === 'XOR' && isXYWire(gate.in1) && isXYWire(gate.in2)) {\n   234→      const xMatch = gate.in1.match(/^x(\\d+)$/) ?? gate.in2.match(/^x(\\d+)$/);\n   235→      if (xMatch) {\n   236→        const bit = parseInt(xMatch[1]);\n   237→        if (bit > 0) {\n   238→          // This gate should output the partial sum, but outputs a z-wire.\n   239→          // Find who outputs zN: it should be a XOR gate.\n   240→          const zN = `z${pad(bit)}`;\n   241→          const zGate = byOut.get(zN);\n   242→          if (zGate && zGate.op === 'XOR') {\n   243→            // zGate's inputs include the partial sum.\n   244→            // One of its inputs should be gate.out (but it's wrong) —\n   245→            // find which input is NOT the carry and should be the partial.\n   246→            // The partial candidate: the input that is NOT a carry (OR output).\n   247→            // Actually, one of zGate's inputs is the wrong partial name (= gate.out = z-wire).\n   248→            // Wait, no: zGate's inputs are the ORIGINAL names. If the partial was swapped\n   249→            // from \"t01\" to \"z01\", then zGate still reads \"t01\".\n   250→            // So zGate.in1 or zGate.in2 = \"t01\" (original partial name).\n   251→            // And gate.out = \"z01\" (swapped name of partial).\n   252→            // The swap pair: \"z01\" (gate.out) <-> \"t01\" (what zGate reads as partial)\n   253→            const in1Gate = byOut.get(zGate.in1);\n   254→            const in2Gate = byOut.get(zGate.in2);\n   255→            // The partial input should come from a XOR(xN,yN)-like gate... actually\n   256→            // it could be any intermediate wire. The carry input comes from OR.\n   257→            // Identify which of zGate's inputs is the carry (comes from OR or AND).\n   258→            let partnerWire: string | undefined;\n   259→            if (in1Gate?.op === 'OR' || (in1Gate?.op === 'AND' && isXYWire(in1Gate.in1))) {\n   260→              partnerWire = zGate.in2; // in2 is the partial\n   261→            } else if (in2Gate?.op === 'OR' || (in2Gate?.op === 'AND' && isXYWire(in2Gate.in1))) {\n   262→              partnerWire = zGate.in1; // in1 is the partial\n   263→            } else {\n   264→              // Can't determine easily; both might be wrong\n   265→            }\n   266→            if (partnerWire && !swapped.has(partnerWire)) {\n   267→              swapped.add(partnerWire);\n   268→              partnered.add(w);\n   269→              partnered.add(partnerWire);\n   270→            }\n   271→          }\n   272→        }\n   273→      }\n   274→    }\n   275→\n   276→    // Pattern: OR gate outputs z-wire (wrong carry output)\n   277→    if (gate.op === 'OR') {\n   278→      // Find the correct carry wire: it should be used by the next bit as carry.\n   279→      // The \"next bit\" final sum XOR has some carry input.\n   280→      // To find: look at what XOR gate is the final sum at next bit.\n   281→      // That XOR's non-partial input is the carry expected.\n   282→      // The OR's z-wire output is swapped with that carry.\n   283→      // But finding the next bit's final sum XOR requires knowing the partial...\n   284→\n   285→      // Simpler: the correct carry wire is NOT a z-wire but IS used somewhere\n   286→      // as a carry input. Find a non-z-wire that feeds into XOR or AND and\n   287→      // that's produced by a gate that should be this carry.\n   288→      //\n   289→      // Actually: if OR outputs z-wire W, then W is swapped with some wire V.\n   290→      // V is flagged too (because byOut.get(V) is some gate that should NOT produce V).\n   291→      // Find V among the flagged wires that isn't a z-wire.\n   292→      for (const w2 of swappedArr) {\n   293→        if (w2 === w || partnered.has(w2)) continue;\n   294→        if (!isZWire(w2)) {\n   295→          // w2 is a non-z wire that's flagged as wrong — it's the partner\n   296→          swapped.add(w2);\n   297→          partnered.add(w);\n   298→          partnered.add(w2);\n   299→          break;\n   300→        }\n   301→      }\n   302→    }\n   303→  }\n   304→\n   305→  return [...swapped].sort();\n   306→}\n   307→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"350d141e-1ad6-4c7b-94f6-5ea915684ec7","uuid":"032692a1-14f9-4cf2-a0d4-63afb93e6eae","tool_use_result":{"type":"update","filePath":"/workspace/src/index.ts","content":"export interface Gate {\n  op: 'AND' | 'OR' | 'XOR';\n  in1: string;\n  in2: string;\n  out: string;\n}\n\nexport function simulate(gates: Gate[], inputs: Record<string, number>): Record<string, number> {\n  const wires: Record<string, number> = { ...inputs };\n  const pending = [...gates];\n\n  let changed = true;\n  while (changed && pending.length > 0) {\n    changed = false;\n    for (let i = pending.length - 1; i >= 0; i--) {\n      const gate = pending[i];\n      if (wires[gate.in1] !== undefined && wires[gate.in2] !== undefined) {\n        const a = wires[gate.in1];\n        const b = wires[gate.in2];\n        let out: number;\n        if (gate.op === 'AND') out = a & b;\n        else if (gate.op === 'OR') out = a | b;\n        else out = a ^ b;\n        wires[gate.out] = out;\n        pending.splice(i, 1);\n        changed = true;\n      }\n    }\n  }\n\n  return wires;\n}\n\nexport function findSwappedWires(gates: Gate[]): string[] {\n  // Strategy: check each gate output for correctness using adder structural rules.\n  //\n  // Rules a correct ripple-carry adder output wire must satisfy:\n  //\n  // 1. zN must be produced by a XOR gate (for 0 <= N <= numBits-1)\n  // 2. z0 must be XOR(x00, y00)\n  // 3. zN (N>0) must be XOR where one input is output of XOR(xN, yN)\n  //    and the other input is a carry wire (from OR or AND-carry-bit0)\n  // 4. No intermediate non-z wire should be the output of a XOR(xN, yN) gate\n  //    that also feeds directly into a z-output XOR... wait, that's circular.\n  //\n  // Simpler structural checks we can apply to each individual wire:\n  //   - A z-wire must come from XOR gate\n  //   - XOR(xN, yN) must not output a z-wire (except z0 from XOR(x0,y0))\n  //   - OR gate must not output a z-wire (except the final carry z(N+1))\n  //   - etc.\n  //\n  // These per-wire checks identify WRONG outputs. We then pair them up as swaps.\n  //\n  // Specifically, the rules for a correct adder:\n  //   For bit 0:\n  //     - z00 is produced by XOR(x00, y00)\n  //   For bit N > 0:\n  //     - zN is produced by XOR gate\n  //     - That XOR's inputs are: XOR(xN,yN).out and some carry wire\n  //     - The carry wire is: output of OR gate (which combines generate and propagate)\n  //     - The OR gate's inputs are: AND(xN,yN).out and AND(XOR(xN,yN).out, carry).out\n  //\n  // Violations: any wire that fails these checks is wrong.\n  //\n  // Per-gate structural rules we can check without knowing wire names:\n  //\n  // RULE 1: If a gate is XOR(xN, yN), its output should NOT be a z-wire\n  //         (because XOR(xN,yN) is the \"partial sum\", not the final sum)\n  //         EXCEPTION: for bit 0, XOR(x00,y00) -> z00 IS correct.\n  //         Wait no, even for bit 0, XOR(x00,y00) -> z00 is correct.\n  //         For bit N > 0, XOR(xN,yN) -> partialN (not zN).\n  //\n  // RULE 2: If a gate is OR, its output should NOT be a z-wire\n  //         (carry wires should be intermediate, not output bits)\n  //         EXCEPTION: the final carry OR at bit numBits-1 outputs z(numBits).\n  //         We can identify the final carry OR: it's the OR gate whose output\n  //         is z(numBits). So ANY other OR gate outputting a z-wire is wrong.\n  //\n  // RULE 3: If a gate is AND, its output should NOT be a z-wire\n  //         (AND outputs are intermediate: generate or propagate)\n  //\n  // These rules give us gates with WRONG outputs. Each wrong output is part of a swap.\n  // We need to find the pairs.\n  //\n  // Additional rule:\n  // RULE 4: If a gate is XOR(xN, yN) for N > 0, its output feeds a XOR gate.\n  //         If the XOR(xN,yN) output doesn't feed any XOR gate, it's wrong.\n  //         (The partial sum must feed the final sum XOR.)\n  //\n  // RULE 5: The gate producing zN (N > 0) must be a XOR gate whose inputs are:\n  //         - output of XOR(xN, yN) — the partial sum\n  //         - some carry wire (not x, y, z named)\n  //\n  // Implementation plan:\n  //   1. Find all gates with \"wrong\" outputs (violate rules)\n  //   2. Each wrong output is in a swap pair\n  //   3. To find the partner: the wrong gate's output is the name of a \"correct\"\n  //      wire that's being used elsewhere, and vice versa\n  //\n  // Simpler: use the per-bit analysis but with a smarter carry tracking.\n\n  // Build lookup\n  const byOut = new Map<string, Gate>();\n  for (const g of gates) byOut.set(g.out, g);\n\n  function findGate(op: Gate['op'], w1: string, w2: string): Gate | undefined {\n    return gates.find(g =>\n      g.op === op &&\n      ((g.in1 === w1 && g.in2 === w2) || (g.in1 === w2 && g.in2 === w1))\n    );\n  }\n\n  let numBits = 0;\n  for (const gate of gates) {\n    for (const w of [gate.in1, gate.in2]) {\n      const m = w.match(/^x(\\d+)$/);\n      if (m) numBits = Math.max(numBits, parseInt(m[1]) + 1);\n    }\n  }\n\n  function pad(n: number) { return String(n).padStart(2, '0'); }\n  function isZWire(w: string) { return /^z\\d+$/.test(w); }\n  function isXYWire(w: string) { return /^[xy]\\d+$/.test(w); }\n\n  const swapped = new Set<string>();\n\n  // Check each gate output for violations\n  for (const gate of gates) {\n    const out = gate.out;\n    const in1 = gate.in1;\n    const in2 = gate.in2;\n\n    // RULE: XOR gate reading (xN, yN) for N > 0 should NOT output a z-wire\n    if (gate.op === 'XOR' && isXYWire(in1) && isXYWire(in2)) {\n      const xMatch = in1.match(/^x(\\d+)$/) ?? in2.match(/^x(\\d+)$/);\n      if (xMatch) {\n        const bit = parseInt(xMatch[1]);\n        if (bit > 0 && isZWire(out)) {\n          swapped.add(out);\n        }\n      }\n    }\n\n    // RULE: OR gate should NOT output a z-wire (except the final carry)\n    if (gate.op === 'OR' && isZWire(out)) {\n      // Check if it's the final carry: final carry = z(numBits)\n      const finalCarry = `z${pad(numBits)}`;\n      if (out !== finalCarry) {\n        swapped.add(out);\n      }\n    }\n\n    // RULE: AND gate should NOT output a z-wire\n    if (gate.op === 'AND' && isZWire(out)) {\n      swapped.add(out);\n    }\n  }\n\n  // Now check z-wires: each zN should be produced by the right type of gate\n  for (let bit = 0; bit < numBits + 1; bit++) {\n    const zN = `z${pad(bit)}`;\n    const gate = byOut.get(zN);\n    if (!gate) continue;\n\n    if (bit === 0) {\n      // z00 must come from XOR(x00, y00)\n      if (!(gate.op === 'XOR' && isXYWire(gate.in1) && isXYWire(gate.in2))) {\n        swapped.add(zN);\n      }\n    } else if (bit === numBits) {\n      // Final carry must come from OR gate\n      if (gate.op !== 'OR') {\n        swapped.add(zN);\n      }\n    } else {\n      // zN (0 < N < numBits) must come from XOR gate\n      if (gate.op !== 'XOR') {\n        swapped.add(zN);\n      }\n      // And that XOR must have one input from XOR(xN, yN)\n      if (gate.op === 'XOR') {\n        const xN = `x${pad(bit)}`;\n        const yN = `y${pad(bit)}`;\n        const gateA = findGate('XOR', xN, yN);\n        if (gateA) {\n          // One of gate.in1, gate.in2 should be gateA.out\n          if (gate.in1 !== gateA.out && gate.in2 !== gateA.out) {\n            swapped.add(zN);\n          }\n        }\n      }\n    }\n  }\n\n  // The wrongly identified wires must be in swap pairs.\n  // Some already have partners (e.g., OR outputs z-wire: that z-wire is also flagged).\n  // Find the partners for any remaining unfound swaps.\n  // Since we know exactly 4 pairs, we should have 8 wires total.\n  // But we might have some without partners explicitly found.\n  //\n  // For each wrong wire, find its swap partner:\n  // - If wire W has wrong output from gate G, the correct output for G is some wire X\n  //   where X is being produced by a different gate that \"should\" produce W.\n  //\n  // More specific: if the z00 gate is not XOR(x00,y00), then the correct gate for z00\n  // is XOR(x00,y00), which is outputting some wrong wire. That wrong wire is z00's swap.\n\n  // Find partners for orphaned swapped wires\n  const swappedArr = [...swapped];\n  const partnered = new Set<string>();\n\n  for (const w of swappedArr) {\n    if (partnered.has(w)) continue;\n    // Try to find its swap partner\n    const gate = byOut.get(w);\n    if (!gate) continue;\n\n    // For each flagged wire, determine what the gate SHOULD output:\n    // If gate is OR and wrongly outputs z-wire, it should output a carry.\n    // The correct carry wire is the one that the next bit's final sum XOR reads.\n    // If gate is AND and outputs z-wire, it should output an intermediate.\n    // If z-wire is produced by wrong gate type, the correct gate is the one that\n    // produces the \"correct\" wire.\n\n    // Pattern: XOR(xN,yN) outputs z-wire → swapped with some non-z wire\n    // that XOR(xN,yN) should output.\n    // That non-z wire is the one actually used as partial sum.\n    // How to find it: look for what feeds into the final sum XOR at bit N.\n    // The final sum XOR for bit N: XOR gate outputting zN.\n    // It has two inputs: one is some non-x,y wire (the partial), one is carry.\n    // The partial should be XOR(xN,yN).out.\n\n    if (gate.op === 'XOR' && isXYWire(gate.in1) && isXYWire(gate.in2)) {\n      const xMatch = gate.in1.match(/^x(\\d+)$/) ?? gate.in2.match(/^x(\\d+)$/);\n      if (xMatch) {\n        const bit = parseInt(xMatch[1]);\n        if (bit > 0) {\n          // This gate should output the partial sum, but outputs a z-wire.\n          // Find who outputs zN: it should be a XOR gate.\n          const zN = `z${pad(bit)}`;\n          const zGate = byOut.get(zN);\n          if (zGate && zGate.op === 'XOR') {\n            // zGate's inputs include the partial sum.\n            // One of its inputs should be gate.out (but it's wrong) —\n            // find which input is NOT the carry and should be the partial.\n            // The partial candidate: the input that is NOT a carry (OR output).\n            // Actually, one of zGate's inputs is the wrong partial name (= gate.out = z-wire).\n            // Wait, no: zGate's inputs are the ORIGINAL names. If the partial was swapped\n            // from \"t01\" to \"z01\", then zGate still reads \"t01\".\n            // So zGate.in1 or zGate.in2 = \"t01\" (original partial name).\n            // And gate.out = \"z01\" (swapped name of partial).\n            // The swap pair: \"z01\" (gate.out) <-> \"t01\" (what zGate reads as partial)\n            const in1Gate = byOut.get(zGate.in1);\n            const in2Gate = byOut.get(zGate.in2);\n            // The partial input should come from a XOR(xN,yN)-like gate... actually\n            // it could be any intermediate wire. 