wire, and our current gate reads A.out... nope, our gate\n   117→      // reads gate.out (an intermediate), not A.out (z-wire).\n   118→      //\n   119→      // The key link: gate.out = original A.out. A.out was swapped with z-wire Z.\n   120→      // Now A.out = Z. AND gate reads gate.out = original A.out.\n   121→      // So: gate.in1 or gate.in2 = gate.out = original A.out.\n   122→      // We need to find A (which now outputs Z instead of gate.out).\n   123→      // A is the XOR(xN,yN) gate for some bit N.\n   124→      // A.out = Z (z-wire).\n   125→      // The correct z-wire for that bit is zN. If A.out = zN, then z-wire is\n   126→      // its own bit's z — special case. If A.out = different z-wire, it's a general case.\n   127→      //\n   128→      // For simplicity: iterate all XOR(xN,yN) gates for N>0, find any with a z-wire output.\n   129→      // For each such gate A with A.out = Z (z-wire):\n   130→      //   Check if there's a gate B reading A.out (= Z) as input... no, because A.out changed.\n   131→      //   Actually: does gate B read the original A.out (= gate.out)?\n   132→      //   gate.out = original A.out. So our gate B reads gate.out = original A.out.\n   133→      //   B and A: A.out should be gate.out but is Z. B reads gate.out but gate.out ≠ A.out.\n   134→      //\n   135→      // This means Z and gate.out are swapped: Z → gate.out, gate.out → Z.\n   136→      //\n   137→      // So for our gate, we look for a XOR(xN,yN) gate whose output is a z-wire.\n   138→      // That z-wire and gate.out are the swap pair.\n   139→      //\n   140→      // But there might be multiple XOR(xN,yN) gates with z-wire outputs.\n   141→      // We need to find the specific one that corresponds to THIS gate.\n   142→      // Hint: both gates belong to the SAME bit N.\n   143→      // Bit N: gateA = XOR(xN,yN) → Z (wrong). gateB = our gate → gate.out (wrong).\n   144→      // gateB reads gate.out (= original gateA.out) and carry as inputs.\n   145→      //